1. Overgeneralization

Original idea:
"When I came to Tokyo, I was so surprised by the locals' heart-warming welcome, and making friends was easy."

Problem:
Your personal experience is treated as if it will happen to everyone.

Why it is weak:
Different people may have different experiences depending on personality, school environment, and location.

Better logic:
"My experience in Tokyo was positive, so I hope you will also find it easy to make friends."

---

2. Unsupported prediction

Original idea:
"You might even become one of the most popular students because of your unique identity."

Problem:
Being new or having a unique identity does not automatically make someone popular.

Why it is weak:
Popularity depends on many factors, such as personality, communication skills, and shared interests.

Better logic:
"Your unique background could help you make interesting connections with others."

---

3. Ignoring possible difficulties

Original idea:
"I see nearly no disadvantages to living in a new area."

Problem:
You dismiss possible challenges.

Why it is weak:
Moving can involve problems such as homesickness, adapting to a new culture, or difficulty making friends.

Better logic:
"Although moving can be challenging at first, it also brings many opportunities."

---

4. Minimization of bullying

Original idea:
"I almost got bullied because I was Chinese, but it all settled down, so it is also not a big deal."

Problem:
Your conclusion does not fully match the seriousness of the issue.

Why it is weak:
Even if your situation improved, bullying can still be a serious concern for others.

Better logic:
"I experienced some difficulties at first, but things improved over time. Remember that you can seek help if you face similar problems."

---

5. Repetition of reassurance

Original idea:
"Just relax, everything will be fine and just relax..."

Problem:
The conclusion gives reassurance without adding practical advice.

Better logic:
"Stay positive, be open to new experiences, and don't hesitate to ask for help if needed."